          </li>
<li id="2012" class="selected">
    <img src='/images/Malala Yousafzai.jfif'/>
    <h1>2012</h1>
    <h2>Malala Yousafzai</h2>
    <p>Malala Yousafzai is an advocate for female education and the youngest nobel prize laureate.
        In early 2009 at just 11 years old she wrote anonlymously for BBC Urdu about her life under during the pakastani
        taliban occupation of swat. She rose to prominence in the news, and was nominated for a children's Peace prize by
        Desmond Tutu. On 9th October 2012 while on a bus after taking an exam, herself and two other females were shot by
        a Pakastani Taliban Gunman in retaliation to her activism. Malala was shot in the head. Following her recovery in the uk
        she co-funded the 'Malala fund' and became a education rights hero. She finished her high school education and went to 
        oxford university.
    </p>
</li>
<li id="2014" class="selected">
    <img src='/images/Emma Watson.jkij'/>
    <h1>2014</h1>
    <h2>Emma Watson</h2>
    <p>Emma Watson was named on of the 100 most influential people in the world by time magazine in 2015. As well as being a 
        child star in the famous harry potter blockbusters, she is well known for her women's rights work. In 2014 she was 
        appointed a UN goodwill Ambassador and helped to launch the UN campaign HeForShe, which advocates for gender equality.
        Watson was appointed to a G7 advisory body for womens' rights in 2019, and consulted with leaders on foreign policy. She 
        has travelled to places like bangladesh and zambia promoting education for girls, ANd made her famous address at the UN 
        Headquarters in New York City, where she questioned gender-based assumptions, and inspired many girls to be proud to call 
        themselves a feminist. 
    </p>
</li>
